<DocsLayout title="Architecture" description="Architecture decisions for Tidal Brewing — introducing Terraform, AWS infrastructure, and Infrastructure as Code.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Architecture</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same process — prompt, template, review. But this architecture document has a new section that dwarfs the others: <strong class="text-text">infrastructure</strong>. For the first time, the architecture covers not just what the application does, but what it runs on and how that infrastructure is created.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is the PRD and design spec for Tidal Brewing, a brewery and taproom management system:

[Paste your PRD here]
[Paste your design spec here]

Using the following architecture template, create a complete technical architecture document.

Tech stack: React frontend, FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, Docker, Nginx reverse proxy.
Infrastructure: AWS (EC2 t2.micro, S3, VPC, security groups), Terraform for provisioning.
Secrets: AWS Secrets Manager (not .env files).
Monitoring: CloudWatch for EC2 metrics, CloudWatch Logs for application logs.

Key architecture decisions to address:
1. Terraform configuration — what resources to create and why
2. VPC and security group setup — which ports are open and to whom
3. EC2 instance configuration — Docker, Nginx, application containers
4. S3 for static assets — images, event photos
5. AWS Secrets Manager for production secrets
6. CloudWatch monitoring — which metrics, what alarms
7. Database backup strategy
8. Application architecture (React + FastAPI + PostgreSQL — same as previous projects)

[Paste architecture template here]`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Infrastructure as Code</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the headline concept for Project 6. Until now, you clicked buttons in a hosting dashboard or ran a deploy command. Terraform changes that fundamentally.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">What Terraform is</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You write <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">.tf</code> files describing the infrastructure you want. An EC2 instance with this size. An S3 bucket with this name. A security group allowing traffic on these ports. Terraform reads those files, compares them to what currently exists in AWS, and creates, updates, or destroys resources to match.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The infrastructure is <strong class="text-text">declared</strong>, not <strong class="text-text">clicked</strong>. Instead of navigating the AWS console and clicking "Launch Instance," you write a file that says "I want an instance with these properties." The file lives in git, gets reviewed in PRs, and can be reproduced exactly on any AWS account.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Why IaC</h3>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Reproducible:</strong> Run <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform apply</code> on a fresh AWS account and get the exact same infrastructure. No "I think I set that up manually last time."</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Version controlled:</strong> Infrastructure changes tracked in git. You can see who changed what, when, and why — just like application code.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Reviewable in PRs:</strong> Infrastructure changes go through the same PR review process as code changes. "This PR adds a new security group rule opening port 8080" — visible, reviewable, approvable.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Destroyable:</strong> <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform destroy</code> tears down everything cleanly. No orphaned resources charging you money because you forgot to delete them in the console.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">The plan/apply cycle</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Terraform has a two-step process that acts as a safety net:</p>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text"><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform plan</code></strong> — Shows what Terraform will do. "I'm going to create 1 EC2 instance, 1 S3 bucket, 1 security group." Nothing happens yet. This is the preview.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text"><code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">terraform apply</code></strong> — Actually creates the resources. Terraform asks for confirmation before proceeding.</li>
  </ol>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Treat <code>terraform plan</code> like a PR review.</strong> Before you apply, read the plan. What's being created? What's being destroyed? Any surprises? A plan that says "destroy 1 EC2 instance" when you expected "create 1 S3 bucket" means something is wrong. Don't apply until the plan matches your expectations.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Key infrastructure decisions</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">These decisions flow directly from Jake's infrastructure requirements in the PRD:</p>

