          <td class="px-4 py-3">Static assets</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">S3 bucket</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Beer images, event photos. Cheaper and faster than serving from EC2.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Networking</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">VPC with public subnet</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Single public subnet. The EC2 instance needs to be internet-accessible.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Firewall</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Security group</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Port 80 (HTTP), 443 (HTTPS), 22 (SSH — restricted to your IP).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Reverse proxy</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Nginx</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Routes traffic to the correct container. Handles SSL termination.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Secrets</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">AWS Secrets Manager</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Database password, API keys. Not in .env files on the server.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3">Monitoring</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">CloudWatch</td>
